{"key":"post-9004902","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9004902</id>\n<content>I absolutely hate the pillow case tek.&amp;nbsp; The excess moisture rarely drains out entirely by gravity, leaving it too wet unless you squeeze it out afterwards.&amp;nbsp; In addition, you leave the substrate hanging overnight exposed to mold spores, which land on your pasteurized substrate material and grow.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I'd suggest pasteurizing in mason jars in a large pot of water.&amp;nbsp; This way, you get the moisture content right before you pasteurize, and you can even seal up the jars to prevent the entry of competitor organisms.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>9003987</prev>\n<first>9002662</first>\n<last>9004902</last>\n<when>1222741252</when>\n<utime>09/30/08 05:20 AM</utime>\n</post>"}